VOYAGER I

It is a artificial satellite launched by NASA on Sept. 5th, 1977; as a part of the Voyager program to study the outer Solar System & the interstellar space beyond the sun's heliosphere. It was launched 16 days after its twin, Voyager II.

VOYAGER II

It is an artificial satellite launched by NASA on August 20, 1977; as a part of the Voyager program to study the outer solar system & the interstellar space beyond the sun's heliosphere. It was launched in Titan IIIE.

FUN FACT: NASA will be able to communicate with the Voyager spacecraft for another 20 years, or until their radioactive power sources can no longer supply enough power.

JUPITER

It is a gas giant and the largest planet in the Solar System. It has a giant storm raging for about two centuries and it's diameter is about the same as 3 Earths. It is called Great Red Spot. It has 95 moons with Ganeymede being the largest. Ganeymede is larger than Mercury.

FUN FACT: Jupiter has a ring around it made up of dust which is not visible to unaided eye.

URANUS

It is a gas giant,seventh planet from the sun and third largest in the solar system. It is second coldest planet with an average temperature of -328 degrees celcius. It also has a very faint ring not visible to unaided eye.

FUN FACT: Wind speeds in Uranus are faster than a commercial airplane.

Q/A ABOUT SPACE

Q1) How is time bent by gravity?

Ans) Gravity bends time by warping spacetime, and the stronger the gravity, the more time slows down.The presence of mass and energy warps spacetime, and the most intense part of that warping is in time. This is known as gravitational time dilation.

Q: What is a black hole?

A: A black hole is a region in space where the gravitational pull is so strong that nothing, not even light, can escape from it. This occurs when a massive star collapses under its own gravity, compressing its mass into an extremely small area. The boundary around a black hole, beyond which nothing can escape, is called the "event horizon."

Q: How far away is the nearest star to Earth?

A: The nearest star to Earth (other than the Sun) is Proxima Centauri, which is about 4.24 light-years away from us. A light-year is the distance light travels in one year, roughly 5.88 trillion miles (9.46 trillion kilometers).

Q: What is dark matter?

A: Dark matter is a form of matter that doesn't emit, absorb, or reflect light, making it invisible and detectable only through its gravitational effects on visible matter. It is thought to make up about 27% of the universe's total mass and energy, but its exact nature remains a mystery.

Q: What is the largest planet in our solar system?

A: Jupiter is the largest planet in our solar system. It has a diameter of about 88,846 miles (142,984 kilometers) and is more than 11 times the size of Earth in diameter. Jupiter is a gas giant, primarily made of hydrogen and helium.

Q: How long does it take for light from the Sun to reach Earth?

A: It takes about 8 minutes and 20 seconds for light from the Sun to travel to Earth. The distance from the Sun to Earth is approximately 93 million miles (150 million kilometers), which is known as 1 Astronomical Unit (AU).
